istories during the 1992 Los Angeles riots; and analyzing the 1996 hostage takeover of the Japanese ambassador's home in Peru. Kim highlights how the aesthetic and creative work of the Japanese and Korean diasporas offers new insights into twenty-first-century concerns surrounding the state's erasure of military violence and colonialism and the difficult work of remembering histories of war across the transpacific.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aAsian diaspora. 0aAsianszUnited States. 0aDecolonizationzPacific Area. 0aGriefxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aImperialism. 0aPostcolonialism and the artszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Asian American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2019z978311069632540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478002796zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478002796423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781478002796.jpg  a978-3-11-069632-5  DUK eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles